# CLAUDE.md

> Generic idastone template. Drop this at the root of your project as
> `CLAUDE.md`, then edit the `Project` section at the bottom with your
> specifics. The sections above the divider are the idastone harness
> contract — don't rip them out unless you know what you're disabling.

## Where things go (plug-and-play map)

| Location | Status | What lives here |
|---|---|---|
| `CLAUDE.md`, `README.md`, `STATE.md`, `ARCHITECTURE.md`, `EXPERIMENT_LOG.md` | **TRACKED** | Public project docs, agent-readable. |
| `.claude/hooks/`, `.claude/scripts/`, `.claude/skills/` | **TRACKED** | Harness logic — edits are shared with collaborators. |
| `.claude/settings.json` | **TRACKED** | Hook registrations. |
| `.claude/settings.local.json` | gitignored | Your personal permission allowlist. |
| `.claude/memory/workflow.db` | gitignored | Per-project learnings/queue/journal state. |
| `.claude/.state/` | gitignored | Sentinels, pids, locks. |
| `.claude/autopilot.conf`, `.claude/budget.toml` | gitignored | Shell-sourced configs — security-critical, never commit. |
| `.claude/_local/` | gitignored | **Agent scratch.** Draft plots, temp notes, in-progress findings. Use freely. |
| `_private/` at any depth | gitignored | **User-confidential** — NDA material, unreleased results, lab internals. |
| `docs/_internal/` | gitignored | Your roadmap / competitive positioning / anything not for outside eyes. |
| `*.private.md` | gitignored | One-off confidential docs alongside regular ones. |
| `experiment-runs/` | user choice | Typically tracked (reproducibility), but gitignore it if runs contain sensitive data. |
| `checkpoints/`, `wandb/`, `mlruns/`, `*.pt`, `*.ckpt` | gitignored | ML artifacts — never in the repo. |
| `.env`, SSH keys, credentials | gitignored | Secrets — never in the repo, even if encrypted. |

**If you're unsure where to put something, put it in `.claude/_local/`.**
Nothing under that dir ever touches git.

## Upstream-back — share the wealth

If you discover a harness-level improvement that generalizes beyond this
project (a new hook, a fix to an existing script, a useful skill), emit:

```
[LEARN harness-upstream] <one-line description of the improvement>
```

The `learn-capture.sh` Stop hook files this in the same DB as ordinary
`[LEARN]` blocks, but tagged so `/propose-harness-change` can surface it
later. When the user reviews, you can run `/propose-harness-change` to
package the diff as a PR against the idastone source repo. Other users
of idastone get the benefit; you get credit; the ecosystem grows. See
`CONTRIBUTING.md` for the PR flow.

Guardrail: the agent does NOT auto-push. The Generator/Verifier/Updater
split lives in `.claude/skills/propose-harness-change/SKILL.md`.

## Workflow: Plan → Research → Build → Audit → Run → Assess → Codify

Every cycle should make the next cycle better.

- **Plan:** Talk with the user. Understand the goal before touching code.
- **Research:** Send agents to verify claims and check novelty. Never assert facts without evidence.
- **Build:** Write code. Keep it clean. Comment the non-obvious.
- **Audit:** Send a separate agent to review code before running. Check shapes, gradients, stability. The implementer does not review their own work.
- **Run:** Use the hardware. Parallel experiments when possible.
- **Assess:** Be honest. Negative results are data. Don't spin.
- **Codify:** Update `STATE.md` and `EXPERIMENT_LOG.md`. If you learned a lesson, emit a `[LEARN]` block so it auto-saves to the learnings DB.

## Learnings DB

A SQLite DB at `.claude/memory/workflow.db` persists durable rules, corrections, and gotchas across sessions. Relevant rules auto-inject at prompt time via the `load-relevant-rules.sh` hook.

**When you learn something worth persisting, emit a `[LEARN]` block in your response:**

```
[LEARN] <category>: <one-line rule>
Mistake: <what went wrong>
Correction: <what the right approach is>
```

The `learn-capture.sh` Stop hook parses these, dedupes by `(project, category, rule)`, and inserts. `Mistake:` and `Correction:` are optional but recommended.

## Dead-end registry

When you definitively kill a research direction — you've proven (via experiment, literature, or math) that it will not work — emit a `[DEAD-END]` block so future brainstorm agents don't re-propose it:

```
[DEAD-END] <direction-slug>: <reason it died, specific and falsifiable>
Evidence: <path to EXPERIMENT_LOG entry, run dir, or paper citation>
```

The `deadend-capture.sh` Stop hook inserts it. On any brainstorm-shaped future prompt ("idea", "try", "what if", "explore"), the `load-relevant-deadends.sh` hook FTS5-matches and surfaces relevant dead-ends via stderr.

Use `[DEAD-END]` sparingly — only for directions that are truly, empirically dead. Ordinary "didn't work this time" goes in `[LEARN]`.

## Hypothesis calibration

Every experiment must log a **predicted metric delta** alongside the hypothesis. After the run, the actual delta is diffed. Over time, this reveals whether the agent's priors are getting better or drifting.

Before any experiment, run:

```bash
python3 .claude/scripts/calibration.py add <run_id> "<hypothesis>" <metric> <predicted_delta>
```

After the run:

```bash
python3 .claude/scripts/calibration.py close <run_id> "<hypothesis>" <actual_delta>
```

`calibration.py report` shows the running scorecard: sign-correctness % and mean absolute error.

## Pre-Experiment Checklist (MANDATORY before every experiment)

1. **State the hypothesis in one sentence.** If you can't, don't run it.
2. **Compute FLOPs, memory, and param count on paper.** 10 minutes. No exceptions.
3. **Try to disprove it in 5 minutes.** "Is this known to fail?"
4. **Check the literature first.** Send a research agent BEFORE building.
5. **Design the comparison before the experiment.** What's the baseline? Matched fairly?
6. **Define success criteria.** What improvement justifies the compute cost?
7. **Verify the claim is novel.** Don't claim uniqueness without checking.

## Waterfall for new ideas

Before building ANYTHING, run this waterfall with subagents:

1. **Brainstorm agent:** Generate ideas (read all project docs first).
2. **Research agent:** Validate top ideas against literature, find code.
3. **Attack agent:** Try to kill every idea. Find fatal flaws.
4. **Validation agent:** Address each attack with evidence. Confirm or deny.

Only build what survives all four stages.

## Hard Rules (harness-level)

These are generic, apply to any project using idastone:

- Verify before claiming. Use web search or research agents.
- Audit code with a separate agent before running.
- Smoke test before any real run (forward, backward, gradient check where relevant).
- Dead directions stay dead. Don't revisit archived ideas unless the user asks.
- Save the exact script that was run alongside its results.
- Log everything to a file; produce a human-readable summary at the end.

Additional project-specific Hard Rules go in the `Project` section below.

